White Wines by Victor Jaen

This data set contains several metrics about white wines and a qualitative variable that contains the evaluation of the whine by experts. So right from the start most of the analysis will be oriented in trying to identify what variables are the most important predictor in wine quality. Besides this we will be exploring if within this variable, some relationship exist and hypothesize why this could be.

We can see that all variables are numerical, and I will probably use them as they are. If the need for a categorical one arises I will create it down the line. The other observation is that they have very different ranges and distributions which is expected given the variety of data we have here. All variables seem to be continuous, except for quality, which seems discrete.

I was first interested in quality. The distribution is discrete, but this is expected since the evaluation was given from a discrete range. I will create an additional variable which will divide the wine in bad, average, and good based on the quality. The ranges will be from 0 to 4, 5 to 7 and then 8 to 10 respectively.

I wanted to have quick distribution of all variables. So using the gather function from tidy verse, I created a tidy data set to make the use of ggplot easier.Most of the variables seem to be normally distributed. They had different spreads and a little bit of skewness, but most seem pretty central. Residual sugar is a little skewed so I will have a look on that one.

df %>% ggplot(aes(x=log(residual.sugar))) + geom_histogram(bins = 50)

Using a logarithmic scale we can see actually almost two distributions with a peak close to 0. We are going to have a closer look to this phenomena in the coming sections.

Bivariate Plots Section

It seems that the better wines have lower density, given the similarity of the 7 and 8 quality. Im cautious with the 9 boxplot, since it could be the result of less samples rather than an actual pattern. Just to confirm if this is the case, I will replicate the graph using the quality_group variable created before.

Yes, it seems that good wines have lower density than other ones. An important thing is that this could be result of sample size, there are less good quality wines, hence the distribution is more uniform.

Looking at other variables, I was curious if total sulfur dioxide had some relationship with Sulphates. In this graphs there seems to be a very weak correlation, at least weaker than I expected. (I know chemically they are different compounds, but they usually have some relationship)

df %>% ggplot(aes(x=fixed.acidity,y=citric.acid)) + geom_jitter(alpha=.5)

Looking at the acidity variables, there seems to be some relationship between the citric acid and the fixed acidity. Chemically Im not sure what could be the mechanism happening behind but this seems to be expected. Source (https://www.winespectator.com/drvinny/show/id/Difference-Between-Sulfites-Sulfates-Wine-54706)

df %>% ggplot(aes(x=fixed.acidity,y=pH)) + geom_jitter(alpha=.5) #strongest relationship

Following the same principle of looking at different variables from the output, I wanted to confirm the relationship between pH an acidity. From This graph we can show that there is a decent relationship.

cor(df$fixed.acidity,df$pH)
## [1] -0.4258583

Running the correlation function we see that the value is actually rather low, -0.42.

I was first curios about residual sugar and density since both showed some sort of different relationship vs the rest of the variables. Using geom_smooth there seems to be some sort of proportional relationship between density and the log of residual sugar, and it seems similar across different wine groups. The fact that the average group goes farther is simply more variability within that group.

df %>% ggplot(aes(x=fixed.acidity,y=citric.acid,color=pH)) +  geom_jitter(alpha=0.4) + scale_color_gradientn(colours = terrain.colors(10))

Also following up with pH, as expected there is a relationship between both acidities and pH. The higher the acidity de lower the pH. This may seem

obvious however is always good to confirm in the dataset that the realworld phenonomenas hold true.

df %>% ggplot(aes(x=total.sulfur.dioxide,y=alcohol,color=quality)) + facet_wrap(~quality_group) + geom_point() + scale_color_gradientn(colours = terrain.colors(8))

Also following up with the sulfur impact, I was interested in seeing it compared to alcohol. There does not seems to exist a relationship between alcohol and sulfur dioxide. Rather some sort of limitation, higher content wine seem to have no more than 200 of sulfur dioxide. On the quality side, high quality wines seem be concentrated in a narrower range of sulfur, a around above 10 of alchol content but besides does limit it could vari.
